<body>

<!-- Disease image -->
<div class="card" style="width: 18rem;">
    <div class="card-header text-center">
        Asthma
    </div>
    <img class="card-img-top" src="https://img.webmd.com/dtmcms/live/webmd/consumer_assets/site_images/articles/health_tools/asthma_overview_slideshow/webmd_rm_photo_of_asthma_illustration.jpg" alt="Asthma Picture">
    <div class="card-body">
        Lethal <br>
        <div class="progress">
            <div class="progress-bar bg-info" role="progressbar" style="width: 50%" aria-valuenow="50" aria-valuemin="0" aria-valuemax="100"></div>
        </div>

        Contagious<br>
        <div class="progress">
            <div class="progress-bar bg-info" role="progressbar" style="width: 50%" aria-valuenow="50" aria-valuemin="0" aria-valuemax="100"></div>
        </div>

        Urgent Care<br>
        <div class="progress">
            <div class="progress-bar bg-info" role="progressbar" style="width: 50%" aria-valuenow="50" aria-valuemin="0" aria-valuemax="100"></div>
        </div>

        <hr>

        <!-- MEDICATION -->
        <div class="input-group mb-2">
            <div class="input-group-text">
                <input type="checkbox" aria-label="Checkbox for medication">
            </div>
            &nbsp Medication
        </div>

        <!-- TREATABLE -->
        <div class="input-group mb-2">
            <div class="input-group-text">
                <input type="checkbox" aria-label="Checkbox for treatable">

            </div>
            &nbsp Treatable
        </div>

        <!-- VACCINATION -->
        <div class="input-group mb-2">
            <div class="input-group-text">
                <input type="checkbox" name="my_name_visual_dummy" value="1" checked="checked" disabled="disabled" />

            </div>
            &nbsp Vaccination
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="details">

    <!-- CAUSES -->
    <a href="#causes" class="list-group-item" data-toggle="collapse">
        <i class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right"></i>Causes
    </a>
    <div class="list-group collapse" id="causes">
        Asthma triggers frequently include:
        <li>Allergens such as pollen, dust mites, cockroaches, molds and animal danders</li>
        <li>Irritants in the air, such as smoke, air pollution, chemical fumes and strong odors</li>
        <li>Medications, such as aspirin and acetaminophen</li>
        <li>Extreme weather conditions</li>
        <li>Exercise</li>
        <li>Stress</li>
    </div>


    <!-- SYMPTOMS -->
    <a href="#symptoms" class="list-group-item" data-toggle="collapse">
        <i class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right"></i>Symptoms
    </a>
    <div class="list-group collapse" id="symptoms">
        <li>Breathlessness</li>
        <li>Wheezing</li>
        <li>Tight feeling in the chest, and/or</li>
        <li>Continuing cough</li>
        If you  have all of these symptoms or only a few, and they may come and go, then you may have asthma.
    </div>

    <!-- TREATMENT -->
    <a href="#treatment" class="list-group-item" data-toggle="collapse">
        <i class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right"></i>Treatment
    </a>
    <div class="list-group collapse list-item" id="treatment">
        Quick-relief medicines are taken at the first sign of symptoms for immediate relief:
        <li>Short-acting inhaled beta2-agonists</li>
        <li>Anticholinergics</li>
        <br>
        Both types of drugs are bronchodilators, meaning that they expand the passageways into the lungs (the bronchi), allowing more air in and out and improving breathing. They also help to clear mucus from the lungs by enabling the mucus to move more freely and get coughed out more easily.

        If you have exercise-induced bronchoconstriction (EIB), also known as exercise-induced asthma, your allergist may recommend that you use these medicines before exercise or other strenuous physical activity.

        Quick-relief medicines can stop asthma symptoms, but they do not control the airway inflammation that causes the symptoms. If you find that you need your quick-relief medicine to treat asthma symptoms more than twice a week, or two or more nights a month, then your asthma is not well controlled.
    </div>

    <!-- HISTORY -->
    <a href="#history" class="list-group-item" data-toggle="collapse">
        <i class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right"></i>History
    </a>
    <div class="list-group collapse" id="history">
        Test Item 4
    </div>
</div>




